##NBA War Disease Enters life-and-death hour 8 hour emergency state increases 3 levels in succession

Provide NBA game, Star dynamic, live broadcast preview, video, data, pictures, features, sidelights, equipment and other kinds of massive information.

For eight hours, the NBA epidemic escalated three times, from the start of the open season, to the postponement of the jazz-oklahoma city game because of illness among jazz players, to the announcement that the 2019-20 season was suspended.

Affected by the COVID-19 outbreak, San Francisco has announced a ban on mass activity of more than 1,000 people for at least two weeks. The Golden State Warriors were the first to go, and the China Standard Time game against the nets at home on March 13 was closed to fans.

Then something even worse happened. Players, coaches, and referees walked out before the Jazz's away game against the thunder. The game has been officially postponed due to pre-game illness of players including Goebel, according to OKC's newscaster.

But it wasn't the end. Goebel was diagnosed with a new coronavirus, and the NBA announced a lockout.

Eight hours, and the NBA is upside down.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Curry will not be seen high-fiving fans for a long time

How did the NBA get to this point?

In fact, with the spread of new pneumonia in the world, the postponement of sports games and open competition has long become a worldwide trend. In order to avoid a widespread infection, the NBA is not alone.

The NBA's first response to the new crown outbreak came on March 1, when the NBA issued a statement after communicating with health officials, "The health and safety of our employees, our teams, our players and our fans are paramount, " he said. "We will work with our teams, consult with the CDC and infectious disease experts, and closely monitor the situation. "

On March 3, the NBA sent teams another memo with a series of provisional recommendations, including a reminder that players should use "fist bumps" instead of "high fives" to wave to fans during the new pneumonia epidemic, avoid contact with fans'pens, balls and jerseys. And with NBA officials concerned about the epidemic, joint trials, on-site trials, international scouts and other activities will also be reduced in scope, or even canceled.

On March 7, the NBA again sent teams memos, the first to mention the possibility of "open play, " in which teams are prepared to empty stadiums if necessary and play without fans, and do a good job on the scene of the necessary staff registration.

On March 8, it was reported that the NBA had begun talking about limiting access to the team's locker room to players and staff, and changing media interviews to other forms to protect everyone from the risk of infection.

"AFTER CONSULTING WITH INFECTIOUS DISEASE AND PUBLIC HEALTH EXPERTS, we are negotiating with other sports leagues to protect the health of everyone in the stadium, including our locker room, " NBA spokesman Mike Bass said in a statement at the time

On March 10, the NBA and other four major professional sports leagues officially announced restrictions on media access to the locker room. It was also reported that the League will hold a conference call with team owners on Wednesday local time to discuss contingency plans.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
NBA, NBA, NBA, NBA

At 2:00 a.m. on March 12, San Francisco announced it would ban mass activity of more than 1,000 people for at least two weeks, and the Golden State Warriors held an open court against the nets at home on March 13.

At 8 a.m. on March 12, the thunder's home game against the jazz was postponed after players, coaches and referees walked out because one of the jazz's players was ill.

At 9:30 a.m. on March 12, Jazz Center Goebel was diagnosed with a new coronavirus.

At 9:35 a.m. on March 12, the NBA officially announced a lockout for the 2019-20 season.

The NBA is not alone. In fact, a number of sporting events around the world have been adjusted because of the new pneumonia outbreak.

La Liga and Segunda División will be without fans for at least two weeks, according to the Spanish football league.

The French Football League has said it will play Ligue 2 on an empty pitch until April 15. A similar announcement was made by the Portuguese football league.

The Italian football league said earlier this week that all sporting events, including the Serie A and Olympic qualifiers, would be suspended until April 3, the Italian ski team also decided not to send their skier to Slovenia for the final World Cup of the season.

A number of sporting events, including the Indian Wells Masters, the Grand Prix of America and the UEFA Champions League, have chosen to delay, cancel or leave the field to prevent the spread of the new pneumonia.

Why not bring the shutdown forward?

It's been a long time since the new cap epidemic began to spread around the world and in the United States. Why did the NBA not declare a lockout until China Standard Time?

First, whether it's an open game or a lockout, it would be a huge financial loss for the NBA.

According to Forbes, the NBA earned $8.8 billion in 2018-19, with ticket sales accounting for 22 percent, or $1.94 billion. The 30 teams averaged $64.67 million in ticket sales, averaging 41 home games, $1.58 million per game. Of course, in terms of actual box office revenue per team, due to the strength of the team and the city, there is a clear "rich-poor difference, " the warriors are the 2018-19 season's highest-grossing team, averaging $3.4 million per game, the Knicks, for example, with a big market in New York, averaged $2.9 million per game in 2018-19, while the grizzlies, which are in a small part of the league economy, averaged less than $1 million per game.

There is a difference in the loss of tickets per team for an open game, but on average more than $1.5 million is lost for an open game. While an empty arena game can reduce labor costs by eliminating the need for ticket inspectors, ushers, and beverage and food salespeople, this cost reduction is not as significant as the economic pie of ticket revenue.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
There are still some Americans who don't take care of themselves

Second, lockouts and open court are difficult for many NBA players to accept.

Le Blanc James, for example, said: "I'm not going to play. We should have fans in the stands. I play for them. It makes sense. "

But it's clear that the development of the NCP epidemic has exceeded many people's expectations. James loves his fans, but he also has to think about himself and the health of his fans.

Soon, james Changed his tune: "I really didn't know that this was a case of NPV prevention. I will be disappointed with the empty field, but at the same time, you have to listen to the professionals. If they think it's best for the safety of the players, the safety of the team, the safety of the League, we'll listen."

This is not just any player, this is Le Blanc James, whose attitude is representative of almost all players.

So, although there is a lot of resistance in the open, it is clear that this resistance is getting smaller and smaller.

Then we'll talk about the NBA's choice between postponing games and leaving the field open.

The NBA's nine-year, $24 billion contract with ESPN and TNT, which began in the 2016-17 season, averages $2.67 billion a year, or 30 percent of the NBA's annual revenue. This means that the NBA game, as long as play, there will be a huge audience dividend, and if canceled, the NBA will suffer more than the economic loss of zero ticket revenue.

While the epidemic can be attributed to force majeure, the NBA's contract with broadcasters is complex and can not be easily avoided. "there are a lot of things that could have a ripple effect if the NBA cancels the game, " said Davy Katel, an associate professor of sports business at USC.

The NBA doesn't want to play an open game, but it's the lesser of two evils, and an open game is a much better option than a postponed or canceled game.

In the end, it was the pressure from the government that forced the NBA to go so fast.

Mike, the governor of Ohio, where the Cleveland Cavaliers is located, said he would issue a ban on mass gatherings, banning fans from going to stadiums to watch games.

List of Governors of Washington John Jay said the state was preparing for tens of thousands of new cases of pneumonia based on estimates of disease transmission. That said, it's likely to affect future sporting events in Washington state.

In California, authorities have issued a ban on mass activity of more than 1,000 people for at least two weeks.

GOEBEL's diagnosis was the final Straw for the NBA, and they had no choice.

It's a lockout. What do the players think?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The warriors will play the nets in the open

Before that, players had complained about empty games because they didn't understand how terrible the outbreak was.

It is clear that open play, something that has never happened before, is bound to be contested. After all, Home Court advantage in sports is a huge advantage, and without the support of the audience, home court is almost meaningless.

Trailblazer Star Lillard said: "instead of playing in a gym where there are no fans, we would rather play in our training uniforms. ". If you can't sell tickets, what does that mean? Would you turn on the TV and watch a game without fans?"

Jason Richardson, who joined the Philadelphia 76ers from Miami Heat this season, said: "It's no different when we play the game than when we play the field. We'll call the game ourselves. "

NBA Hall of Famer Charles, now a commentator, and Spurs guard Arif Dirlik Wyett also voiced their opposition.

But it's worth noting that James, who was the first to speak out, has changed his tune.

"You have to listen to the professionals, " James said. "If they think it's best for the safety of the players, the safety of the team, the safety of the League, then we will listen. "

Bulls star La Verne, who shares Lebron's opinion, said: "Our league is closely linked to the fans, but we are afraid of the new coronavirus. "

The Star player Gallinari from Italy has suffered a severe epidemic of new pneumonia in his home country, so he was one of the players who supported the NBA's decision to leave the field: "I've been telling my teammates about what's going on in Italy and I hope they take it seriously. I fully support the League's approach, not only to protect the players, but also to protect the fans and the staff, for everyone's benefit. I certainly don't want the game to be cancelled or empty, but under the circumstances I would support a game without fans because the most important thing right now is to defend."

But now they have to, or willingly, accept the decision to shut down.

Goebel's diagnosis was a blow to all the players, the closest and most vivid example to them -- as if it wasn't a day ago, when Goebel was poking fun at the League's epidemic fighting policies, and now it's a hand on a microphone, he was diagnosed with a new coronavirus.it's a bad thing.

No NBA player wants to be the next Goebel, and hopefully everyone will learn from Goebel's mistakes.
